abstract = {A study, commissioned by the Confederation of European Paper Industries (CEPI), was conducted aiming to provide an estimate of the forest area and wood volume affected by management restrictions imposed by forest protection in Europe. The volume of wood that could not be felled in the protected areas was assessed firstly by estimating unconstrained felling potentials by disregarding all forms of protection or limitations to mobilize these resources. The felling potentials were assumed to be equal to the average net annual increment, because fellings should not generally exceed increment to assure long-term sustainability. The felling restrictions imposed on protected forest areas varied considerably across Europe. On average, 48{\%} of the volume cannot be felled in forest areas protected for biodiversity and 40{\%} in forests protected for landscapes. The study also identified important data gaps that affected the estimates of unavailable wood due to forest protection.},
