@article{White2007,
abstract = {An accuracy assessment is considered the best way to demonstrate the effectiveness with which different data sources and methods may be used to map mountain pine beetle (Dendroctonus ponderosae) red attack damage from remotely sensed data. Simply reporting overall accuracy, however, does not provide sufficient context to evaluate the map product and may misconstrue the accuracy with which red attack damage is detected and mapped. Accuracy assessments are not difficult to undertake, nor should they be difficult to interpret. Several recommendations regarding accuracy assessment were made in the context of mountain pine beetle red attack detection and mapping: (1) ground surveys provide the best source of validation data for not attacked and red attack; however, air photos and helicopter geographical positioning system surveys are viable alternatives; (2) select validation samples that are spatially representative and that are independent from any calibration data used for the classification; (3) select at least 50-100 samples per class for validation. The more samples used, the greater the confidence in the accuracy estimates reported; (4) use equal sample sizes for both not attacked and red attack classes; (5) report the contents of the full error matrix, not just overall accuracy; and (6) report 95{\%} confidence intervals for both overall accuracy and the producer's accuracy for red attack.},
