@article{Day1950,
abstract = {The effect of soil conditions on root development and anchorage against wind-throw in Britain is examined briefly, with reference to recent original observations in that country and work by others in central Europe. The crux is held to be the gripping of an adequate insert mass of soil by the roots. The importance of drainage is brought out, and the danger when exceptional weather makes the critical layers of a soil semi-liquid and unstable. No root disease need be associated with overturning in such conditions. On the other hand, beech on shallow soil over chalk may be wind-thrown through starvation and death of roots running down 5 or 6 ft. into the fissured chalk rock. The physics of ditch draining require study, and so does the ability of various tree species to maintain natural drainage. Where there is special danger of wind-throw it is held that thinning practice should favour deep crowns rather than shallow, and silviculture should favour an irregular rather than an even canopy. Particular types of soil and vegetation in Britain where the danger of wind-throw is high are mentioned, with special reference to spruce (Picea spp.).},
